April 2017 – What Matters?


































Skip to content



What Matters?
Kelly Conway @ Mattersight | Fail












Month: April 2017 


Today’s Volume — And Price Action — Explained 

When the NASDAQ OTC markets opened trading this morning, Mattersight’s  SEC Form S-3 resale registration statement was effective. It actually was declared effective by the SEC, after the markets closed on Wednesday night. So today’s higher volume is likely at least some of those shares, finding new homes.
And the steady down-beat, in MATR’s per share pricing, is likely at least in part the excess supply such an event unleashes on an otherwise rather thinly traded stock.
But to be sure, most of the recent action is likely market dread, over Q1 2017’s impending per share GAAP losses from operations. I’m guessing like $0.20 per share — and it is really just a guess. But I do think that Lake Street’s ($0.15) of GAAP losses is likely far too optimistic.
We will know in about ten days.
 





Stock At $3.25; Q1 2017 Results Call Now May 9, 2017 

Not too much else needs to be said — except that I expect more GAAP losses from operations.
The polly-anna-ish Lake Street Capital Markets analysts have previously called for a loss of only $0.15 per share. I say it will be more like ($0.20/share), on a GAAP basis.
Here’s the item:
…Mattersight announced that it intends to release its first quarter 2017 financial results after the market close on Tuesday, May 9, 2017. Mattersight management also plans to host a conference call at 5:00 p.m. Eastern Time on Tuesday, May 9, 2017.
The conference call and slide presentation will be available at the Investor Relations section of Mattersight’s website at http://www.mattersight.com/about-us/investor-relations/. To listen to the conference call via telephone, please call 800.952.4789 (domestic) or 404.665.9579 (international), conference ID: 10151911.
For those who cannot access the live broadcast, a replay of the conference call will be available beginning approximately two hours after the live call is completed on May 9, 2017, by dialing 855.859.2056 (domestic) or 404.537.3406 (international), conference ID: 10151911….
Be very careful out there. The resale S-3 is not yet effective — that overhang isn’t factored in yet.





[U] Short Interest Is Up 17 Per Cent, Going Into Q1 2017 Results Call… Stock Closes At $3.30 (04.20.2017). 

UPDATED: 04.20.17 @ 4PM EDT — Bob cogently adds the below — and the stock closes at $3.30 today.
…I’d say the short interest position is based on profiting from the likely erosion of value in the loss carry-forward should corporate income tax rates be reduced in the August timeframe. It’s not part of a downside protection scheme. To do that, you need an active options market, of which, there is minimal for MATR.
Add to this the worrying moves in the executive ranks and the shifting storyline, likely foretelling a disappointing Q1….
[End, updated portion.]
In addition, the trading volume “to cover shorts” stands at 22 days — or it would take 22 plus days of ordinary volume trading to cover the number of shares short, in Mattersight at the moment.
Two logical explanations — for the rising short tide — include (i) some of the selling shareholders in the SEC filed Form S-3 may already have arrangements with Craig-Hallum or others, which effectively require those houses to lay off the risk of a market decline, by shorting the stock in advance of S-3 effectiveness; and (ii) more probably, a general lack of confidence in the company’s ability to deliver on its previously announced financial commitments, during Q1 2017.
We will know for certain before too terribly long, but you can run a Google search to find the auto-bot stories on “Mattersight Short Interest”.
They are poorly written, but accurately crunch the daily trading data, on the NASDAQ OTC.
Now you know — be careful out there.





And Now… The Complete Listing Of Private Placement Purchasers — At $3/Share… 


UPDATED: 05.16.2017 @ 6 PM CDT — Hilariously, Mattersight’s lawyers incorrectly reported one of the selling stockholder’s identities — so the company had to file an amended sticker to the prospectus overnight:
…We are filing this prospectus supplement to reflect that the record holder of 100,000 shares of our common stock to be offered for resale under the Prospectus is Patrick Lin, rather than Primarius Capital. The Prospectus inadvertently assigned only beneficial ownership to Mr. Lin when he is in fact the record holder of such shares. This prospectus supplement does not impact any other selling stockholders set forth in the table appearing under the caption “Selling Stockholders” on page 5 of the Prospectus, which we refer to herein as the Selling Stockholder Table….
This is entirely trivial, but emblematic I think — of the lack of careful review, of most sorts — at the company, generally. [End, Updated Portion.]
For existing shareholders, this was [another] slap in the face.
A new round of highly dilutive equity, to select investors, on a private basis — at $3 a share. When the stock was trading on the NASDAQ at around half a buck higher than that. I’ll not list how many shares each proposes to resell, that’s in the S-3 table, as well — I’ll just list how many each bought. But I should say that when the S-3 is declared effective, it is likely there will be downward pressure, on the NASDAQ stock price — for MATR, as a majority have filed for the right to sell all they own.
One might expect that sort of nonsense in a tech start-up, just getting its legs under it — not a seasoned issuer, with 17 years experience as a registered ’34 Act reporting public company. Sheesh.
My formatting isn’t stellar (cleaning it up — on the fly, now), but here are the people and institutions who bought in — at $3 — and how many shares each holds:
