Proxy Is On File At SEC EDGAR Window… 

I’m on the road, so do go read all the piggy payments to the CEO, for yourself. It seems he earned a cash bonus, and more equity bonuses, for missing estimated GAAP LPS  — on the low side (i.e., losses too large) — for three of the last four quarters.
Disgusting. 
Here it is. I’m out until late Friday…





Preposterous! For The Ump-teeth Time, Mattersight To “Revamp” Its Business Model?!? 

VentureBeat is this afternoon reporting the following — in a rather breathless tone, from VP Andrew Traba (and as a side-note — to my eye, that’s another new name, in the Mattersight roster of seemingly endless VPs of… whatever!):
…As people begin to think about how they feel about ads on intelligent assistants, voice analytics company Mattersight is planning to use unique voice signatures to deliver personalized advertisements and bots. Using artificial intelligence to recognize your personality within 30 seconds, Mattersight wants to deliver personalized ads and bots to Amazon Echo, Google Home, and other voice-controlled devices….
“We know how words or language correlate with personality styles. We ultimately think of ourselves fitting into that landscape, as we’re going to train bots how to be empathetic,” said Mattersight VP of data science Andrew Traba.
Mattersight assigns personality profiles to the people who call major brands, and it wants to bring that same service to intelligent assistants, using voice biometrics as an identifier instead of phone numbers….
[As I’ve long intoned, I very sincerely doubt that Google or Amazon need MATR’s algorithms (despite the showy business method patents!) — in order to do this on their own. But whatever. Most of this junk is public domain 1970s NASA tech.]
And, well — I guess this indicates that (once again!) CEO Conway cannot find a path to profitability, on the current business model.
That has been the main business model “only” since 2012-2013. Prior to that, the model from 2007 to 2011 failed (and was largely sold back to the old parent, under the prior eLoyalty name). Prior to that, the pure call center model never delivered a profitable quarter, in what was over a decade.
So here we sit — coming into mid-2017… Mattersight went public in 2000.
And still it has no idea what it will be, if it can ever… grow up. Ugh.
Oh… and… Yes — this is the quarterly “shiny object“, always used to deflect another quarter of GAAP losses per share, as Q1 2017 is closed out this afternoon at 5 PM CDT.
More — over the weekend. I’m off for some outdoor fun!
 





We Said We’d Let You Know… 

…when we felt it likely that Craig-Hallum was ending its role, in stabilizing the market for Mattersight’s common stock, on the NASDAQ OTC, post the private placement of February 23, 2017.
In view of the smallish volumes over the last few days, and generally flat to declining NASDAQ prices, we think the market stabilization effort has gone into hibernation.
Said another way, many of the holders who are friendly to Mattersight, and were looking to change or rearrange their positions, as a result of (or in response to) the highly dilutive 2017 $16 million private placement — have likely now done so.
It is my expectation that if there are short sellers out there, with open option or direct short positions, we will see them emerge in the coming days and weeks.
Next big event: the proxy filing with the SEC’s EDGAR window, which will list any related party transactions in excess of $60,000, and the full orgy of excesses that makes up the executive team’s 2016-2017 compensation package(s).
Onward. Oh, and happy (belated) St. Patrick’s.










